  "texts": [
    "E s asked crowd workers (using the crowdsourcing service Amazon Mechanical Turkfoot_1) to answer the values of how relevant the AI applications by EFF are to each occupation, and integrated them to compute the AI exposure score.According to the original papers, E t is an indicator of \"exposure to automation\", and E s is \"agnostic as to whether AI substitutes for. \"",
    "Both scores are linked to the occupation list from the BLS, making them applicable to our research.",
    "We compute the correlation coefficient between E t and E s and find the coefficient is 0.027 with p = 0.486, meaning that both scores capture different perspectives.",
    "Following [25], this study does \"not distinguish between labor-augmenting or labor-displacing effects, \" and uses them as indicators of the strength of the relationship between AI and occupation.We match our top 30 occupations with their E t and E s. As our occupation list incorporates the Indeed dictionary in addition to the BLS dictionary, 14 occupations are not matched among 30 occupations.",
    "Also, if more than one occupation in BLS is matched, we use their mean scores (e.g., \"designer\" matches both \"Fashion Designers\" and \"Graphic Designers\")."
  ],
